Later, Jesus was dining at the home of Levi. Many tax collectors and "sinners" were eating with him and his disciples. They were part of the large crowds that followed Jesus.
There were some teachers of the law among the Pharisees who saw Jesus eating with "sinners" and tax collectors. They said to his disciples, "Why does he eat with tax collectors and sinners?"
Jesus heard this and said to them, "Those who are well have no need of a physician, but those who are sick. I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance." (Jesus asked about fasting)
John's disciples and the Pharisees fast. People came to Jesus and said, "John's disciples fast, and the disciples of the Pharisees fast. But your disciples do not fast. Why?"
Jesus answered, "How can the guests of the bridegroom fast while the bridegroom is with them? As long as they have the bridegroom with them, they cannot fast.
But the time will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them. On that day they will fast.
People don't sew a new piece of cloth onto old clothes. If they did, the new piece would pull away from the old one. This would increase the tear.
People don't pour new wine into old wineskins. If they do, the wine will burst the skins, and both the wine and the skins will be lost. No, they pour new wine into new wineskins." Jesus, Lord of the Sabbath
On a Sabbath day, Jesus was walking through a wheat field with his disciples. The disciples began to pluck and eat the heads of grain.
They said to Jesus, "Look! Doing that on the Sabbath is against the law. Why do your disciples do such a thing?"
He replied, "Haven't you read what David did? He and his companions were hungry. They needed food.
That was when Abiathar was high priest. David went into the house of God and ate the hallowed bread, which was lawful only for the priests to eat. And he gave some to his men also.
Then Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath.
Therefore the Son of Man is also Lord of the Sabbath.
Healing on Saturday
Once again, Jesus entered the temple. There was a man with a withered and twisted hand.
Some of the Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They were watching him closely. They wanted to see if he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus spoke to the man with the withered and crooked hand, saying to him, "Rise and stand in the midst."
Then Jesus asked them, "What does the law say about what we should do on the Sabbath? Do we do good or evil? Do we save life or kill?" But no one answered.
Jesus looked around in anger and was deeply disturbed because their hearts were hard. Then he said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." He stretched it out, and his hand was restored as good as new.
Then the Pharisees went out and began to plot with the Herodians against Jesus, how to destroy Him. The multitudes were following Jesus.
Jesus walked to the Sea of Galilee with his disciples, and a large crowd from Galilee followed them.
The people heard of all that Jesus was doing. Many came to him from Judea, Jerusalem, and the surrounding regions, as well as from Tyre and Sidon and the areas around the Sea of Galilee.
Due to the crowd, Jesus told his disciples to prepare a small boat for him. This way, people would not crowd around him.
Jesus healed many people. Therefore, the sick were pressing forward to touch him.
When the people with evil spirits saw him, they fell down before him. The spirits cried out, "You are the Son of God!"
But Jesus commanded them not to tell anyone who he was. Jesus appoints the twelve apostles.
Jesus went up a mountain. He called some people to come to him, and they came.
He appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, that they might be with him and he might send them out to preach.
They will have authority to cast out demons.
Jesus called his twelve disciples to him and gave them authority. He gave Simon the name Peter.
There were James, the son of Zebedee, and his brother John. Jesus gave them the name Boanerges, which means Sons of Thunder.
There were also Andrew, Philip, Bartholomew, Matthew, Thomas, and James son of Alphaeus. And there were Thaddeus and Simon the Zealot.
Judas Iscariot was one of them. He was the one who handed Jesus over to his enemies. Jesus and Beelzebul.
Jesus entered a house. Another crowd gathered. It was so large that Jesus and his disciples could not even eat.
His family heard about it. So they went to take care of him. They said, "He is crazy."
Some of the Pharisees who had come from Jerusalem said, "He is driven by Beelzebul! By the prince of demons he drives out demons."
Then Jesus called the people to him and said to them, "How can Satan drive out Satan?"
If a kingdom fights against itself, it cannot stand.
If a family is divided, it cannot stand.
